Do you have evidence that there is <i>not</i> a profound performance difference between virtual and non-virtual methods? Virtual methods require two memory lookups (the vtable address, then the function address) and hence often two cache misses, compared to non-virtual methods which can be static addresses. If you've got a (common in games) loop like:<p><pre><code>  for ( ..some list of 5000 objects.. ) {
    object.update();
  }
</code></pre>
Then those cache misses will add up. That is my experience anyway, though I'll don't have statistics to back it up
